1
00:00:09,583 --> 00:00:11,000
Good evening, Mr. Data.

2
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:12,375
Actually,
good morning, sir.

3
00:00:12,375 --> 00:00:14,041
Ship status is--
No need to report.

4
00:00:14,041 --> 00:00:15,375
I'm just here to do
some work on my own.

5
00:00:15,375 --> 00:00:16,583
Aye, sir.

6
00:00:16,583 --> 00:00:17,959
I'd like to speak
to Professor Mowray

7
00:00:17,959 --> 00:00:19,834
at his archaeological
site on Landris II.

8
00:00:19,834 --> 00:00:21,500
Could you put it through
to my ready room?

9
00:00:21,500 --> 00:00:23,542
I am sorry, sir, but stellar
cartography has requested

10
00:00:23,542 --> 00:00:26,125
a communications blackout
while they run an experiment.

11
00:00:26,125 --> 00:00:27,667
Hmm. How long
will it be?

12
00:00:27,667 --> 00:00:30,875
Another three hours,
22 minutes, sir.

13
00:00:30,875 --> 00:00:32,125
I can override,
if necessary.

14
00:00:32,125 --> 00:00:33,375
No, it's not important.

15
00:00:33,375 --> 00:00:34,875
Aye, sir.

16
00:00:45,875 --> 00:00:47,333
Computer,
display the latest

17
00:00:47,333 --> 00:00:50,333
excavation schematics
on Landris II.

18
00:00:50,333 --> 00:00:53,542
Library computer
is temporarily off-line.

19
00:00:53,542 --> 00:00:54,792
Explain.

20
00:00:54,792 --> 00:00:57,083
Library systems
have been allocated

21
00:00:57,083 --> 00:00:59,375
to stellar cartography.

22
00:00:59,375 --> 00:01:01,542
(<i> sighs</i> )

23
00:01:11,625 --> 00:01:13,375
Tea, Earl Grey.
Hot.

24
00:01:13,375 --> 00:01:15,417
COMPUTER:
Replicator systems
are off-line

25
00:01:15,417 --> 00:01:16,583
at the request of...

26
00:01:16,583 --> 00:01:18,667
BOTH:
stellar cartography.

27
00:01:24,917 --> 00:01:28,583
What could they possibly
be doing down there?

28
00:01:38,792 --> 00:01:40,083
Oh...

29
00:01:40,083 --> 00:01:42,625
In or out-- just
close that door.

30
00:01:44,583 --> 00:01:47,417
And don't move.

31
00:01:47,417 --> 00:01:51,333
It'll take a second
for our eyes to readjust.

32
00:01:51,333 --> 00:01:54,250
Okay.
Elevate to 3.2, Marquez.

33
00:01:54,250 --> 00:01:55,667
MARQUEZ:
Now at 3.2, Commander.

34
00:01:55,667 --> 00:01:58,291
Good. Good.
We can do this.

35
00:01:58,291 --> 00:02:00,250
No, no, no. We're losing
vertical alignment.

36
00:02:00,250 --> 00:02:02,083
Compensate. Compensate!

37
00:02:02,083 --> 00:02:03,333
Compensating.

38
00:02:03,333 --> 00:02:05,709
Gently. Gently, Marquez.
Don't bump it.

39
00:02:05,709 --> 00:02:07,417
(<i> buzzing</i> )

40
00:02:07,417 --> 00:02:10,500
No! No, no, hit the--

41
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:12,542
Oh... oh, forget it.

42
00:02:12,542 --> 00:02:15,917
Forget it.
Lights.

43
00:02:15,917 --> 00:02:17,500
Whoever you are,
you just ruined

44
00:02:17,500 --> 00:02:19,125
four hours of work.

45
00:02:19,125 --> 00:02:20,500
You might have taken
the simple precaution

46
00:02:20,500 --> 00:02:21,667
of locking the door.

47
00:02:21,667 --> 00:02:23,291
It's 3:00
in the morning...

48
00:02:26,166 --> 00:02:27,709
Captain Picard.

49
00:02:27,709 --> 00:02:31,709
I assume that you must be
Lieutenant Commander Daren.

50
00:02:31,709 --> 00:02:33,250
Yes, sir.

51
00:02:33,250 --> 00:02:35,500
I'm sorry. It's just we
weren't expecting anybody

52
00:02:35,500 --> 00:02:37,166
to be up at this hour.

53
00:02:37,166 --> 00:02:40,625
Well, you're new
on the<i> Enterprise.</i>

54
00:02:40,625 --> 00:02:43,583
You'll have to learn
to expect the unexpected.

55
00:02:43,583 --> 00:02:45,542
That's why I put in for
this assignment, sir.

56
00:02:45,542 --> 00:02:47,375
Excellent. Now, perhaps
you can tell me

57
00:02:47,375 --> 00:02:49,041
what was so important
that it required

58
00:02:49,041 --> 00:02:51,542
depriving the captain
of his cup of Earl Grey.

59
00:02:51,542 --> 00:02:55,041
Earl Grey? No wonder
you can't sleep.

60
00:02:55,041 --> 00:02:56,917
Computer, bring replicators
back online

61
00:02:56,917 --> 00:02:58,917
and give me a cup
of Daren herbal tea

62
00:02:58,917 --> 00:03:01,208
blend number three,
hot.

63
00:03:06,375 --> 00:03:07,792
You shouldn't be
drinking a stimulant

64
00:03:07,792 --> 00:03:09,500
at this time of night.

65
00:03:11,291 --> 00:03:13,291
I think
you'll like this.

66
00:03:17,875 --> 00:03:19,917
I-- I've programmed
seven other blends

67
00:03:19,917 --> 00:03:21,750
into the replicator.

68
00:03:21,750 --> 00:03:24,250
You're bound to
like one of them.

69
00:03:24,250 --> 00:03:25,542
I look forward
to sampling them.

70
00:03:25,542 --> 00:03:27,250
(<i> coughing</i> )

71
00:03:27,250 --> 00:03:28,583
(<i> chuckling</i> )

72
00:03:28,583 --> 00:03:30,834
I'm sorry if, uh,
the system blackouts

73
00:03:30,834 --> 00:03:34,375
we requested...
inconvenienced you.

74
00:03:34,375 --> 00:03:36,417
We're taking very precise
gravimetric readings,

75
00:03:36,417 --> 00:03:38,375
so it wouldn't have taken
much to throw them off.

76
00:03:38,375 --> 00:03:40,125
What were
the readings for?

77
00:03:40,125 --> 00:03:42,750
Well, I'm trying to construct
a mathematical model

78
00:03:42,750 --> 00:03:44,625
of an emerging
star system.

79
00:03:44,625 --> 00:03:46,375
If it works, we'll
be able to predict

80
00:03:46,375 --> 00:03:48,000
the configuration
of a star system

81
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,166
that won't be formed for
another two million years.

82
00:03:51,166 --> 00:03:53,834
A long time to wait
to see if you're right.

83
00:03:53,834 --> 00:03:56,792
I have a few things to do
between now and then.

84
00:04:26,917 --> 00:04:31,583
<i>Space, the final frontier.</i>

85
00:04:31,583 --> 00:04:35,834
<i>These are the voyages</i>
<i>of the Starship</i> Enterprise.

86
00:04:35,834 --> 00:04:37,417
<i>Its continuing mission--</i>

87
00:04:37,417 --> 00:04:41,166
<i>to explore</i>
<i>strange new worlds...</i>

88
00:04:41,166 --> 00:04:45,792
<i>to seek out new life</i>
<i>and new civilizations...</i>

89
00:04:45,792 --> 00:04:49,750
<i>to boldly go where</i>
<i>no one has gone before.</i>

90
00:05:51,583 --> 00:05:53,208
Captain, we'll be arriving

91
00:05:53,208 --> 00:05:55,542
at the Borgolis Nebula
in three hours.

92
00:05:55,542 --> 00:05:56,875
Yes, I understand

93
00:05:56,875 --> 00:06:00,417
that it has some unusual
radioactive emissions.

94
00:06:00,417 --> 00:06:01,959
Well, I'm sure that
stellar sciences

95
00:06:01,959 --> 00:06:03,667
will find it a most
interesting study.

96
00:06:03,667 --> 00:06:05,917
Commander Daren has already
requested extra time

97
00:06:05,917 --> 00:06:07,917
on the main
sensor array.

98
00:06:09,917 --> 00:06:11,542
Well, you have the
bridge, Number One.

99
00:06:11,542 --> 00:06:13,000
Captain?

100
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:14,417
I would like
to remind you

101
00:06:14,417 --> 00:06:16,291
of our concert this
evening in Ten Forward.

102
00:06:16,291 --> 00:06:19,041
We will perform Chopin's
"Trio in G Minor."

103
00:06:19,041 --> 00:06:20,917
I'll be there.

104
00:06:26,333 --> 00:06:27,709
PICARD:
And so, the upshot is,

105
00:06:27,709 --> 00:06:29,000
that we'll be close enough
for you to slip away

106
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,375
for a few days
and see Wesley.

107
00:06:30,375 --> 00:06:32,792
Oh, that's wonderful.
Thank you, Jean-Luc.

108
00:06:32,792 --> 00:06:34,583
This is delicious.
What is it?

109
00:06:34,583 --> 00:06:36,834
Mmm, it's
a herbal tea blend.

110
00:06:36,834 --> 00:06:40,709
I, um... found it
in the replicator files.

111
00:06:40,709 --> 00:06:42,417
Oh.

112
00:06:42,417 --> 00:06:43,917
Have you met any
of the new crew members

113
00:06:43,917 --> 00:06:46,166
who came aboard
at Starbase 218?

114
00:06:46,166 --> 00:06:48,166
In fact, I have
a new nurse-- Beck.

115
00:06:48,166 --> 00:06:50,458
He's an obstetrics
specialist.

116
00:06:50,458 --> 00:06:54,250
I met the new head
of stellar sciences last night--

117
00:06:54,250 --> 00:06:56,250
Lieutenant Commander Daren.

118
00:06:56,250 --> 00:06:58,625
Yes...
Nella Daren.

119
00:06:58,625 --> 00:07:00,709
She came into sick bay
for a physical last week.

120
00:07:00,709 --> 00:07:02,917
I like her--
very forthright.

121
00:07:03,834 --> 00:07:06,125
Did you know...

122
00:07:06,125 --> 00:07:07,542
that it is now possible

123
00:07:07,542 --> 00:07:11,041
to predict the configuration
of a star system

124
00:07:11,041 --> 00:07:13,375
which won't be formed
for another two million years?

125
00:07:13,375 --> 00:07:15,166
Really?
No, I didn't.

126
00:07:15,166 --> 00:07:17,375
Mm-hmm. It's really
quite intriguing.

127
00:07:17,375 --> 00:07:19,000
The whole thing
is made possible

128
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:21,792
by a complex
mathematical construct

129
00:07:21,792 --> 00:07:24,125
based on fractal
particle motion.

130
00:07:24,125 --> 00:07:25,750
But that's only
the foundation.

131
00:07:25,750 --> 00:07:29,792
The modeling itself is done
by gravimetric wave input.

132
00:07:30,667 --> 00:07:33,417
I see.
Hmm.

133
00:07:33,417 --> 00:07:35,208
Well...

134
00:07:35,208 --> 00:07:37,291
I know this is all
pretty dry stuff.

135
00:07:39,125 --> 00:07:42,166
Stellar cartography
isn't everybody's cup of tea.

136
00:07:42,166 --> 00:07:44,166
I'm sure it's really
quite fascinating.

137
00:07:45,667 --> 00:07:47,583
You know, we should be
getting along to Ten Forward.

138
00:07:47,583 --> 00:07:49,291
We're going to be late
for the concert.

139
00:07:54,083 --> 00:07:59,250
(<i> audience murmuring</i> )

140
00:08:06,417 --> 00:08:10,125
(<i> door opens, closes</i> )

141
00:08:21,792 --> 00:08:25,250
(<i> playing Chopin's</i>
<i>"Trio in G Minor"</i> )

142
00:09:30,709 --> 00:09:32,208
Thank you.
DAREN: Thank you.

143
00:09:32,208 --> 00:09:34,542
Will you
excuse me?

144
00:09:34,542 --> 00:09:36,667
Yes,
of course.

145
00:09:36,667 --> 00:09:38,667
Well done, Mr. Data.
Well done.

146
00:09:38,667 --> 00:09:40,333
Commander, that was
a remarkable performance.

147
00:09:40,333 --> 00:09:42,625
You are very talented.
Thank you.

148
00:09:42,625 --> 00:09:44,291
I noticed that the
applause this evening

149
00:09:44,291 --> 00:09:46,417
exceeded average
decibel levels.

150
00:09:46,417 --> 00:09:48,125
I guess that means
they enjoyed themselves.

151
00:09:48,125 --> 00:09:49,583
I think that much
was obvious.

152
00:09:49,583 --> 00:09:50,834
Excuse me.
I have not yet

153
00:09:50,834 --> 00:09:53,125
congratulated
Ensign Cheney.

154
00:09:53,125 --> 00:09:54,917
I'll go with you.

155
00:09:54,917 --> 00:09:57,041
Commander, you must have been
playing since you were young.

156
00:09:57,041 --> 00:09:59,041
I played the piano
for a while when I was small,

157
00:09:59,041 --> 00:10:01,667
but I didn't put in
the practice you must have.

158
00:10:01,667 --> 00:10:03,417
Well, practicing was
never my problem.

159
00:10:03,417 --> 00:10:07,250
In fact, my parents had to
make me go out and play.

160
00:10:07,250 --> 00:10:08,875
I wanted to ask,
uh...

161
00:10:08,875 --> 00:10:10,792
during the second arpeggio
of the first movement,

162
00:10:10,792 --> 00:10:12,125
I noticed that you played

163
00:10:12,125 --> 00:10:14,458
an F minor chord
instead of a diminished D.

164
00:10:14,458 --> 00:10:16,166
You're a musician.
What's your instrument?

165
00:10:16,166 --> 00:10:17,417
We should play sometime.

166
00:10:17,417 --> 00:10:19,083
No, no, no.
I'm-I'm just an amateur.

167
00:10:19,083 --> 00:10:21,750
But your choice in that
arpeggio was delightful.

168
00:10:21,750 --> 00:10:24,250
Not at all
what one would expect.

169
00:10:24,250 --> 00:10:25,834
Well, Captain,
now that I'm on your ship,

170
00:10:25,834 --> 00:10:30,083
maybe you should start
expecting the unexpected.

171
00:10:40,917 --> 00:10:43,458
Ah.
Excuse me, sir.

172
00:10:43,458 --> 00:10:45,875
I was hoping that my people
in spectral analysis

173
00:10:45,875 --> 00:10:48,333
could have another few hours
on the main sensor array?

174
00:10:48,333 --> 00:10:49,834
I'm sorry.
The array has already

175
00:10:49,834 --> 00:10:51,125
been allocated
to engineering.

176
00:10:51,125 --> 00:10:52,417
They're running
some warp field tests.

177
00:10:52,417 --> 00:10:54,208
If we go off-line
now, we'll lose

178
00:10:54,208 --> 00:10:56,417
the gas flow pattern
we've been tracking.

179
00:10:56,417 --> 00:10:58,083
I understand, but there are
other departments

180
00:10:58,083 --> 00:11:00,458
waiting to use the array.

181
00:11:00,458 --> 00:11:03,041
We're at a critical
juncture, sir.

182
00:11:03,041 --> 00:11:05,542
(<i> firmly</i> )
Commander...

183
00:11:05,542 --> 00:11:07,166
(<i> sighs</i> )

184
00:11:07,166 --> 00:11:08,333
I'll see what I can do
to find you

185
00:11:08,333 --> 00:11:09,583
some more time
tomorrow.

186
00:11:09,583 --> 00:11:11,208
Tomorrow?
Tomorrow.

187
00:11:11,208 --> 00:11:13,000
Mm-hmm.

188
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:15,083
Thank you, sir.

189
00:11:17,583 --> 00:11:21,542
(<i> flute playing Bach's</i>
<i>"Third Brandenburg Concerto" )</i>

190
00:11:21,542 --> 00:11:23,041
(<i> door chimes</i> )

191
00:11:23,041 --> 00:11:25,208
Computer, pause playback.
Come.

192
00:11:27,291 --> 00:11:29,875
Oh... Commander Daren.

193
00:11:29,875 --> 00:11:32,125
I hope you don't mind me
dropping by like this?

194
00:11:32,125 --> 00:11:34,458
No. Please, come in.
I'm delighted.

195
00:11:36,709 --> 00:11:39,250
What kind of
a flute is that?

196
00:11:39,250 --> 00:11:41,792
It's, uh...
Ressikan.

197
00:11:41,792 --> 00:11:43,291
I've never
seen one before.

198
00:11:45,041 --> 00:11:46,542
They're not made
any more.

199
00:11:48,750 --> 00:11:51,041
have you been playing long?

200
00:11:51,041 --> 00:11:53,542
Um...

201
00:11:53,542 --> 00:11:55,917
yes, a long time.

202
00:11:55,917 --> 00:11:58,250
I'd love to hear you
play sometime.

203
00:11:58,250 --> 00:12:00,041
I'm not very good.

204
00:12:00,041 --> 00:12:02,709
Well, that doesn't matter,
as long as you enjoy it.

205
00:12:02,709 --> 00:12:04,291
Yes, but I wouldn't
want to inflict it

206
00:12:04,291 --> 00:12:06,291
on someone else.

207
00:12:06,291 --> 00:12:07,542
May I try?

208
00:12:07,542 --> 00:12:09,458
Yes, of course.

209
00:12:13,875 --> 00:12:16,166
Hmm, now...

210
00:12:17,750 --> 00:12:19,917
Yes, you're-- you're not
holding it quite right.

211
00:12:19,917 --> 00:12:22,542
May I?
Please.

212
00:12:26,792 --> 00:12:30,917
(<i> playing slow melody</i> )

213
00:12:46,917 --> 00:12:48,625
You're-- You're better
than you think.

214
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:51,458
Really!

215
00:12:51,458 --> 00:12:52,834
We should play together.

216
00:12:52,834 --> 00:12:55,208
Uh... there
isn't a piano.

217
00:12:55,208 --> 00:12:57,375
Ah, but there<i> is.</i>

218
00:13:01,625 --> 00:13:03,542
I picked it up
on Mataline II.

219
00:13:03,542 --> 00:13:05,458
It's amazing.

220
00:13:05,458 --> 00:13:08,250
(<i> plays ascending arpeggio</i> )

221
00:13:08,250 --> 00:13:10,208
That is remarkable.

222
00:13:10,208 --> 00:13:12,458
Well, why don't<i> you</i> 
play something?

223
00:13:12,458 --> 00:13:15,250
You start,
and I'll jump in.

224
00:13:15,250 --> 00:13:16,667
What should we play?

225
00:13:16,667 --> 00:13:19,250
What were you working on
before I came in?

226
00:13:19,250 --> 00:13:21,417
Um, Bach,
the "Third Brandenburg."

227
00:13:21,417 --> 00:13:23,583
perfect.

228
00:13:23,583 --> 00:13:25,250
Go ahead.

229
00:13:25,250 --> 00:13:27,792
(<i> sighs, clears throat</i> )

230
00:13:29,542 --> 00:13:31,625
(<i> plays opening melody</i> )

231
00:13:37,542 --> 00:13:39,417
Uh... I'm sorry.

232
00:13:40,625 --> 00:13:43,792
Oh. It's all right.

233
00:13:43,792 --> 00:13:46,166
You're not used to playing
with anyone, are you?

234
00:13:46,166 --> 00:13:47,875
Just the computer.

235
00:13:47,875 --> 00:13:49,667
Hmm.

236
00:13:49,667 --> 00:13:51,792
Well, I may not be
as precise as a computer,

237
00:13:51,792 --> 00:13:55,959
but... well, I think
you'll enjoy it more.

238
00:13:55,959 --> 00:13:57,208
Uh, why don't we start

239
00:13:57,208 --> 00:13:58,667
with something
a little simpler.

240
00:13:58,667 --> 00:14:00,250
How about...

241
00:14:00,250 --> 00:14:03,125
(<i> slowly playing</i>
<i>"Frere Jacques"</i> )

242
00:14:06,333 --> 00:14:11,208
(<i> both playing "Frere Jacques"</i>
<i>in round form</i> )

243
00:14:27,333 --> 00:14:28,542
Good!

244
00:14:28,542 --> 00:14:30,000
Very good.

245
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:31,667
Now, let's have
a little fun with it.

246
00:14:31,667 --> 00:14:36,083
(<i> playing improvised version</i>
<i>of "Frere Jacques"</i> )

247
00:14:42,959 --> 00:14:44,166
Go on, you try it.

248
00:14:44,166 --> 00:14:45,542
Improvise around
the melody--

249
00:14:45,542 --> 00:14:48,291
anything
you want.

250
00:14:48,291 --> 00:14:51,709
(<i> playing improvised version</i>
<i>of "Frere Jacques"</i> )

251
00:14:54,500 --> 00:14:56,208
Good.

252
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:02,000
That's wonderful.

253
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,750
Keep going.

