this afternoon.

262
00:16:15,959 --> 00:16:17,750
I was wondering if you
wanted to join me.

263
00:16:17,750 --> 00:16:19,000
Fencing?
Mm-hmm.

264
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:20,417
I'm not really
very good.

265
00:16:20,417 --> 00:16:21,917
Ah, it doesn't matter
so long as you...

266
00:16:21,917 --> 00:16:23,583
ch-ch-ch-ch...
(<i> clicking</i> )

267
00:16:23,583 --> 00:16:25,709
Enjoy it.

268
00:16:25,709 --> 00:16:27,834
Why not?
Good! Excellent.

269
00:16:27,834 --> 00:16:29,834
1400 hours, then.

270
00:16:35,041 --> 00:16:37,291
You have a mild strain.
Oh.

271
00:16:37,291 --> 00:16:39,917
I've been playing
the piano a lot.

272
00:16:39,917 --> 00:16:43,083
I guess the captain and I
overdid it a little last night.

273
00:16:43,083 --> 00:16:44,291
The captain?

274
00:16:44,291 --> 00:16:45,625
Yes, he plays
a kind of flute...

275
00:16:45,625 --> 00:16:48,458
um, a Ressikan,
I think he said.

276
00:16:48,458 --> 00:16:51,625
Yes, but I didn't know
he played duets.

277
00:16:51,625 --> 00:16:54,417
Well, he never
did before.

278
00:16:54,417 --> 00:16:56,291
He seemed
to enjoy it.

279
00:16:56,291 --> 00:16:57,959
He's actually
quite promising.

280
00:16:57,959 --> 00:16:59,667
I see.

281
00:17:02,208 --> 00:17:04,333
Tell me, have you
known him long?

282
00:17:05,458 --> 00:17:07,875
Yes, a very long time.

283
00:17:09,500 --> 00:17:12,417
He seems...

284
00:17:12,417 --> 00:17:14,500
somewhat isolated.

285
00:17:15,792 --> 00:17:17,500
I'd say he's
a very private person,

286
00:17:17,500 --> 00:17:19,792
but not isolated.

287
00:17:19,792 --> 00:17:21,834
There,
that should help.

288
00:17:21,834 --> 00:17:24,333
Hmm, that feels
much better.

289
00:17:24,333 --> 00:17:26,208
Thank you.
Good.

290
00:17:26,208 --> 00:17:29,291
I was afraid
I might have to cancel.

291
00:17:29,291 --> 00:17:31,959
Another duet?

292
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,709
Keep climbing.

293
00:17:38,709 --> 00:17:40,417
Where are we going?

294
00:17:40,417 --> 00:17:42,208
We're almost there.

295
00:17:42,208 --> 00:17:45,709
I don't see why we couldn't
just practice in my quarters.

296
00:17:52,917 --> 00:17:54,709
(<i> sighs</i> )

297
00:18:09,917 --> 00:18:11,208
Do you know
where we are?

298
00:18:11,208 --> 00:18:13,375
Uh, yes. This is
the fourth intersect

299
00:18:13,375 --> 00:18:15,083
in Jefferies tube 25.

300
00:18:15,083 --> 00:18:16,792
No... this is the most

301
00:18:16,792 --> 00:18:20,291
acoustically perfect spot
on the ship.

302
00:18:20,291 --> 00:18:24,125
(<i> playing "Moonlight Sonata"</i> )

303
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:38,458
The intersection acts
as a resonance chamber.

304
00:18:38,458 --> 00:18:39,959
How did you find it?

305
00:18:39,959 --> 00:18:41,417
A little exploring.

306
00:18:41,417 --> 00:18:42,792
You mean to say
that you crawled through

307
00:18:42,792 --> 00:18:44,875
every tube on the ship?

308
00:18:44,875 --> 00:18:47,375
Well, not every one.

309
00:18:50,458 --> 00:18:52,417
Try it.
See how it sounds.

310
00:18:59,375 --> 00:19:04,041
(<i> Picard playing melody</i>
<i>from "Inner Light"</i> )

311
00:19:19,500 --> 00:19:21,792
That's beautiful.

312
00:19:21,792 --> 00:19:23,125
What is it?

313
00:19:23,125 --> 00:19:25,208
It's, um...

314
00:19:25,208 --> 00:19:27,875
an old folk melody.

315
00:19:27,875 --> 00:19:30,500
I've never heard you play
with such feeling.

316
00:19:34,125 --> 00:19:37,458
(<i> picking out notes</i>
<i>of "Inner Light" melody</i> )

317
00:19:39,041 --> 00:19:41,792
(<i> Daren adding chords</i>
<i>to song</i> )

318
00:19:51,750 --> 00:19:55,583
(<i> Picard picks up melody</i>
<i>on flute</i> )

319
00:20:25,250 --> 00:20:29,417
(<i> distant music playing</i> )

320
00:20:52,667 --> 00:20:54,792
(<i> music stops</i> )

321
00:20:56,583 --> 00:20:58,458
is there a problem,
Geordi?

322
00:20:58,458 --> 00:21:00,083
I hear music.

323
00:21:00,083 --> 00:21:02,083
Music?

324
00:21:04,083 --> 00:21:05,291
I do not hear anything.

325
00:21:05,291 --> 00:21:06,667
You sure?
Mm.

326
00:21:06,667 --> 00:21:09,458
I know I heard
something.

327
00:21:09,458 --> 00:21:12,750
Hmm...
it stopped.
Hmm.

328
00:21:23,291 --> 00:21:26,291
I'd heard about Kerelian
tenors all my life,

329
00:21:26,291 --> 00:21:28,375
but nothing could
have prepared me

330
00:21:28,375 --> 00:21:30,208
for this man's
voice.

331
00:21:30,208 --> 00:21:32,208
Soaring,
incredible range.

332
00:21:32,208 --> 00:21:33,959
Hmm.
Wonderful.

333
00:21:33,959 --> 00:21:35,625
I understand
that there are nuances

334
00:21:35,625 --> 00:21:37,208
that only Kerelians
can pick up.

335
00:21:37,208 --> 00:21:39,542
We just don't have
the ears for it.

336
00:21:39,542 --> 00:21:41,458
Mmm.

337
00:21:44,291 --> 00:21:45,542
I should be
finished with

338
00:21:45,542 --> 00:21:48,542
my survey
by 1100 hours.

339
00:21:48,542 --> 00:21:50,542
(<i> brusquely</i> )
Very good, Commander.

340
00:22:01,458 --> 00:22:04,291
Captain, the Federation
outpost on Bersallis III

341
