510
00:30:19,667 --> 00:30:23,417
within eight hours
and are requesting evacuation.

511
00:30:23,417 --> 00:30:25,375
I'm on my way.

512
00:30:31,542 --> 00:30:35,125
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 46693.1:</i>

513
00:30:35,125 --> 00:30:37,542
<i>We have entered</i>
<i>the Bersallis star system</i>

514
00:30:37,542 --> 00:30:39,750
<i>and are making</i>
<i>preparations to evacuate</i>

515
00:30:39,750 --> 00:30:42,291
<i>the Federation outpost</i>
<i>on the third planet.</i>

516
00:30:42,291 --> 00:30:43,750
A firestorm can
kick up winds

517
00:30:43,750 --> 00:30:45,750
of over 200
kilometers per hour

518
00:30:45,750 --> 00:30:48,083
and temperatures
as high as 300 degrees C.

519
00:30:48,083 --> 00:30:49,834
Incredible.
What causes them?

520
00:30:49,834 --> 00:30:53,041
They form when
solar flare radiation

521
00:30:53,041 --> 00:30:54,417
reacts with
high-energy plasma

522
00:30:54,417 --> 00:30:56,208
present in
the planet's atmosphere.

523
00:30:56,208 --> 00:30:59,333
Wasn't the outpost constructed
to<i> withstand</i> the conditions?

524
00:30:59,333 --> 00:31:01,750
It was-- both reinforced
and insulated.

525
00:31:01,750 --> 00:31:03,375
But this is
no ordinary storm.

526
00:31:03,375 --> 00:31:05,959
It's twice as strong
as anything they've ever seen.

527
00:31:05,959 --> 00:31:07,709
The outpost just
won't withstand it.

528
00:31:07,709 --> 00:31:09,750
We'll arrive about an hour
before the storm gets there,

529
00:31:09,750 --> 00:31:11,417
and it'll take us
at least two hours

530
00:31:11,417 --> 00:31:14,041
to evacuate the colonists
off the surface.

531
00:31:14,041 --> 00:31:15,750
I led a team of geologists

532
00:31:15,750 --> 00:31:18,125
to study the plasma geyser
on Melnos IV.

533
00:31:18,125 --> 00:31:21,125
Now, we cross-connected
a few thermal deflector units

534
00:31:21,125 --> 00:31:23,333
to create a protective shield
against the heat.

535
00:31:23,333 --> 00:31:24,709
A firewall.

536
00:31:24,709 --> 00:31:27,000
Mm-hmm. Would something
like that work here?

537
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:30,792
You know... it might.

538
00:31:30,792 --> 00:31:34,458
The storm is approaching the
outpost from this direction.

539
00:31:36,041 --> 00:31:38,917
If we were to set up a series
of thermal deflector units

540
00:31:38,917 --> 00:31:41,542
along the northern perimeter,
we could create a firewall

541
00:31:41,542 --> 00:31:43,375
and deflect
some of the heat.

542
00:31:43,375 --> 00:31:44,750
The insulation
from the outpost

543
00:31:44,750 --> 00:31:46,041
should be able
to handle the rest.

544
00:31:46,041 --> 00:31:47,792
Thermal deflectors
generate a field

545
00:31:47,792 --> 00:31:50,083
approximately
400 meters wide.

546
00:31:50,083 --> 00:31:52,333
We would need to
cross-connect six units

547
00:31:52,333 --> 00:31:54,458
and align them so that
the fields overlap.

548
00:31:54,458 --> 00:31:56,834
How many people would
it take to set that up?

549
00:31:56,834 --> 00:31:58,667
Twelve-- two per team.

550
00:31:58,667 --> 00:32:01,000
Cross-connecting that many
units, it'll be a little tricky.

551
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:03,583
Once they're set up, we'll have
to leave the units in place

552
00:32:03,583 --> 00:32:05,041
and transport our people out.

553
00:32:05,041 --> 00:32:06,667
Nobody would be able
to survive

554
00:32:06,667 --> 00:32:09,417
very long outside
that structure.

555
00:32:10,792 --> 00:32:12,542
Let's do it.

556
00:32:12,542 --> 00:32:14,458
The storm is going to
interfere with communication.

557
00:32:14,458 --> 00:32:16,667
Everything will need to be
coordinated from the surface.

558
00:32:16,667 --> 00:32:19,125
Mr. Data, you will coordinate
the evacuation of the colonists.

559
00:32:19,125 --> 00:32:21,458
Doctor, there are nine patients
in the outpost infirmary.

560
00:32:21,458 --> 00:32:23,500
Your first priority will be
to get them to Sick Bay.

561
00:32:23,500 --> 00:32:25,417
After that, you will stay
on board the<i> Enterprise.</i>

562
00:32:25,417 --> 00:32:27,166
Be ready to receive
casualties.

563
00:32:27,166 --> 00:32:29,959
Marquez, you'll take some people
down and track the storm.

564
00:32:29,959 --> 00:32:32,333
All the other teams will need to
be kept apprised of its heading.

565
00:32:32,333 --> 00:32:35,291
Commander, you'll be in charge
of deploying the deflectors.

566
00:32:35,291 --> 00:32:37,333
Let's go.

567
00:32:38,750 --> 00:32:41,208
Commander Daren?

568
00:32:42,917 --> 00:32:45,083
About those
thermal deflectors.

569
00:32:47,834 --> 00:32:49,625
There must be one
of any number of people

570
00:32:49,625 --> 00:32:51,291
that coordinate
their deployment.

571
00:32:51,291 --> 00:32:54,709
I assume Commander
Riker chose me

572
00:32:54,709 --> 00:32:57,583
because I'm the best
person for the job.

573
00:32:57,583 --> 00:32:59,834
Didn't we agree not
to let our relationship

574
00:32:59,834 --> 00:33:02,041
get in the way
of our work?

575
00:33:05,542 --> 00:33:07,375
I'll be all right.

576
00:33:27,959 --> 00:33:30,250
Lieutenant Marquez is already
set up on the surface.

577
00:33:30,250 --> 00:33:32,208
Apparently, the storm
is gaining speed.

578
00:33:32,208 --> 00:33:33,792
He's estimating
it'll hit the colony

579
00:33:33,792 --> 00:33:35,542
in less than
50 minutes.

580
00:33:35,542 --> 00:33:37,667
Ensign, make sure you maintain
a continuous transporter lock

581
00:33:37,667 --> 00:33:39,375
on all away team
personnel.

582
00:33:39,375 --> 00:33:41,208
We may have to pull
them out in a hurry.
ENSIGN: Aye, sir.

583
00:33:41,208 --> 00:33:43,834
RIKER: I don't want to take any
unnecessary chances down there.

584
00:33:43,834 --> 00:33:46,166
If anyone gets into trouble
beam them up immediately.

585
00:33:46,166 --> 00:33:48,250
Energize.

586
00:34:04,667 --> 00:34:08,208
Mr. Worf, how long until
the storm reaches the outpost?

587
00:34:08,208 --> 00:34:09,834
17 minutes.

588
00:34:09,834 --> 00:34:13,250
La Forge to Bridge.
Go ahead, Mr. La forge.

589
00:34:13,250 --> 00:34:15,333
The ionization from
the storm is interfering

590
00:34:15,333 --> 00:34:17,083
with the transporters,
Captain.

591
00:34:17,083 --> 00:34:20,083
I'm compensating, but it's
slowing things down a bit.

592
00:34:20,083 --> 00:34:21,792
PICARD:
Keep at it, Mr. La Forge.

593
00:34:36,959 --> 00:34:39,625
RIKER:
Riker to Daren.

594
00:34:39,625 --> 00:34:41,458
Daren here.
Go ahead, Commander.

595
00:34:41,458 --> 00:34:43,458
RIKER: You've got less than
nine minutes before the storm

596
00:34:43,458 --> 00:34:45,542
reaches
the northern perimeter.

597
00:34:45,542 --> 00:34:47,041
I'm here with team six.

598
00:34:47,041 --> 00:34:49,000
We're just about to bring
the deflectors online.

599
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:52,000
RIKER:
Whenever you're ready.

600
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:53,291
Daren to perimeter teams.

601
00:34:53,291 --> 00:34:55,542
Stand by to
cross-connect deflectors.

602
00:34:55,542 --> 00:34:58,041
MAN: Standing by.
Activate.

603
00:35:05,792 --> 00:35:08,709
Team three, increase your
output by point two percent.

604
00:35:08,709 --> 00:35:11,250
WOMAN: Yes, sir.
Good, good.

605
00:35:12,834 --> 00:35:16,333
Deng, decrease nutation
by point four percent.

606
00:35:17,291 --> 00:35:20,375
Good.
We've almost got it.

607
00:35:26,250 --> 00:35:29,041
Crusher to Bridge.
Go ahead, Doctor.

608
00:35:29,041 --> 00:35:31,125
We just brought back the last
of the infirmary patients

609
00:35:31,125 --> 00:35:32,709
and they're on
their way to Sick Bay,

610
00:35:32,709 --> 00:35:35,208
but we still have over
100 colonists down there.

611
00:35:35,208 --> 00:35:37,458
Understood.

612
00:35:37,458 --> 00:35:40,875
Daren to Commander Riker.
Riker here. Go ahead.

613
00:35:40,875 --> 00:35:42,667
DAREN:
We've got a problem.

614
00:35:42,667 --> 00:35:45,542
We're having trouble keeping
the deflectors cross-connected.

615
00:35:45,542 --> 00:35:47,000
So, the only way
this is going to work

616
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:49,041
is if we calibrate
them manually.

617
00:35:49,041 --> 00:35:50,542
RIKER:
If you stay with the deflectors,

618
00:35:50,542 --> 00:35:52,333
will they protect you
when the storm hits?

619
00:35:52,333 --> 00:35:55,291
DAREN:
I don't know, sir.

620
00:35:55,291 --> 00:35:57,083
A few minutes maybe.

621
00:35:57,083 --> 00:35:59,041
(<i> static hissing</i> )

622
00:35:59,041 --> 00:36:00,959
Picard to Commander Riker.

623
00:36:00,959 --> 00:36:05,125
How many more colonists
do you have to transport?
73, sir.

624
00:36:05,125 --> 00:36:08,208
How long do you need?
At least ten more minutes.

625
00:36:08,208 --> 00:36:10,875
Captain,
the storm will reach

626
00:36:10,875 --> 00:36:12,875
the northern perimeter
in four minutes.

627
00:36:19,625 --> 00:36:21,709
Picard to perimeter teams.

628
00:36:21,709 --> 00:36:26,166
It is imperative
that you hold your position

629
00:36:26,166 --> 00:36:29,417
until we've finished
evacuating the colony.

630
00:36:29,417 --> 00:36:31,417
Picard out.

631
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:36,250
Picard to Mr. La Forge.
La Forge here.

632
00:36:36,250 --> 00:36:38,333
I want a signal lock

633
00:36:38,333 --> 00:36:40,041
on every member
of the perimeter teams.

634
00:36:40,041 --> 00:36:42,750
LA FORGE: Captain, the storm's
interference won't...

635
00:36:42,750 --> 00:36:44,917
As soon as the last
of the colony is evacuated,

636
00:36:44,917 --> 00:36:46,500
I want those
perimeter teams out of there.

637
00:36:46,500 --> 00:36:48,875
Is that understood?
Yes, sir.

638
00:36:48,875 --> 00:36:50,041
(<i> electrical zapping</i> )

639
00:36:50,041 --> 00:36:51,792
(<i> wind howling</i> )

640
00:36:53,083 --> 00:36:55,208
Daren to perimeter teams.

641
00:36:55,208 --> 00:36:56,959
The storm's interference

642
00:36:56,959 --> 00:36:59,458
is going to make our job
harder than we thought.

643
00:36:59,458 --> 00:37:01,208
We may lose communication,

644
00:37:01,208 --> 00:37:04,750
so it's up to each of you to
keep your units operational.

645
00:37:06,417 --> 00:37:10,041
A lot of people
are depending on us.

646
00:37:10,041 --> 00:37:12,083
Daren out.

647
00:37:26,208 --> 00:37:27,959
Oh, my God.

648
00:37:27,959 --> 00:37:29,792
(<i> wind roaring</i> )

649
00:37:33,375 --> 00:37:35,667
The storm has reached
the perimeter.

650
00:37:46,250 --> 00:37:48,542
(<i> murmuring voices</i> )

651
00:37:54,458 --> 00:37:57,000
I got out with
the last of the colonists.

652
00:37:57,000 --> 00:37:59,083
If it hadn't been
for the perimeter teams,

653
00:37:59,083 --> 00:38:01,125
none of us would
have made it.

654
00:38:01,125 --> 00:38:03,125
We were able to clear
out four of the teams

655
00:38:03,125 --> 00:38:06,208
and the interference prevented
us from getting two more.

656
00:38:06,208 --> 00:38:08,709
I don't know how
they could have survived.

657
00:38:12,834 --> 00:38:15,083
Which teams are missing?

658
00:38:15,083 --> 00:38:17,959
Three and six.

659
00:38:17,959 --> 00:38:21,542
The last I knew,
Commander Daren
was on team six.

660
00:39:07,917 --> 00:39:10,583
WORF:
Bridge to Captain.

661
00:39:10,583 --> 00:39:12,333
Go ahead, Mr. Worf.

662
00:39:12,333 --> 00:39:14,250
WORF:
We have found survivors, sir.

663
00:39:14,250 --> 00:39:16,291
They are beaming up now.

664
00:39:19,375 --> 00:39:20,917
I'm on my way.

665
00:39:20,917 --> 00:39:23,458
(<i> indistinct voices</i> )

666
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:42,041
(<i> whoosh of</i>
<i>active transport</i> )

667
00:39:52,166 --> 00:39:53,834
That's it.

668
00:39:56,291 --> 00:39:58,458
Here, let me help you.
Thank you.

669
00:39:58,458 --> 00:40:00,959
Here, just give
me your hands.

670
00:40:00,959 --> 00:40:02,500
You're going to be fine.

671
00:40:05,709 --> 00:40:10,125
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 46697.2:</i>

672
00:40:10,125 --> 00:40:11,792
<i>Although we succeeded</i>
<i>in rescuing</i>

673
00:40:11,792 --> 00:40:14,458
<i>all 643 Bersallin colonists,</i>

674
00:40:14,458 --> 00:40:16,625
<i>we lost eight crew members.</i>

675
00:40:16,625 --> 00:40:19,333
<i>Let the record show</i>
<i>that they gave their lives</i>

676
00:40:19,333 --> 00:40:21,291
<i>in the performance</i>
<i>of their duty.</i>

677
00:40:21,291 --> 00:40:23,417
When communications
went out,

678
00:40:23,417 --> 00:40:26,000
I knew we had to fend
for ourselves.

679
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:28,959
We modified our phasers
to create resonant disruptions

680
00:40:28,959 --> 00:40:30,417
in the deflector field.

681
00:40:30,417 --> 00:40:32,125
The disruptions
formed small pockets

682
00:40:32,125 --> 00:40:33,959
in the plane
of the field

683
00:40:33,959 --> 00:40:38,375
and we each stood inside one
to wait out the storm.

684
00:40:38,375 --> 00:40:41,333
Richardson
didn't make it.

685
00:40:41,333 --> 00:40:45,041
All Deng and I could do
was stand there...

686
00:40:45,041 --> 00:40:47,083
and watch.

687
00:40:50,208 --> 00:40:51,375
I'm so sorry.

688
00:40:51,375 --> 00:40:53,375
Don't, don't say
you're sorry.

689
00:40:58,500 --> 00:41:00,875
It must have been terrible.

690
00:41:02,834 --> 00:41:05,333
At first, when you told us
to hold our positions,

691
00:41:05,333 --> 00:41:07,000
I didn't question it.

692
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:08,375
Of course we would.

693
00:41:08,375 --> 00:41:10,458
That was our job.

694
00:41:11,917 --> 00:41:15,125
But when I saw that storm
coming toward us...

695
00:41:17,166 --> 00:41:20,542
A part of you
must have blamed me.

696
00:41:20,542 --> 00:41:23,792
A small part, maybe.

697
00:41:25,208 --> 00:41:27,083
But, in the end,
I was more afraid

698
00:41:27,083 --> 00:41:29,750
that you'd blame yourself
if I died.

699
00:41:35,500 --> 00:41:37,500
Would you have?

700
00:41:39,750 --> 00:41:43,166
I've lost people
under my command...

701
00:41:43,166 --> 00:41:45,542
people who were
very dear to me...

702
00:41:48,166 --> 00:41:50,000
but never...

703
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:52,917
someone I've been
in love with.

704
00:41:52,917 --> 00:41:56,417
And when I believed
that you were dead,

705
00:41:56,417 --> 00:41:58,166
I just began to shut down.

706
00:41:58,166 --> 00:42:01,458
I didn't want
to think or feel.

707
00:42:01,458 --> 00:42:03,917
I was here in my quarters...

708
00:42:07,500 --> 00:42:10,750
and the only thing I could
focus on was my music

709
00:42:10,750 --> 00:42:13,583
and how it would never again
give me any joy.

710
00:42:16,083 --> 00:42:19,875
And then I saw you standing
on the transporter pad.

711
00:42:22,500 --> 00:42:24,792
And I knew that I could

712
00:42:24,792 --> 00:42:27,583
never again put
your life in jeopardy.

713
00:42:32,083 --> 00:42:34,458
If I stayed here...

714
00:42:34,458 --> 00:42:37,083
you might have to.

715
00:42:37,083 --> 00:42:40,208
You could always resign
your commission.

716
00:42:40,208 --> 00:42:41,750
Stay here with me.

717
00:42:41,750 --> 00:42:44,000
And you could
resign yours

718
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:47,667
and come to
a starbase with me.

719
00:42:47,667 --> 00:42:51,000
(<i> chuckles</i> )

720
00:42:57,667 --> 00:42:59,458
I'll apply...

721
00:42:59,458 --> 00:43:01,542
for a transfer.

722
00:43:06,792 --> 00:43:09,333
But we could
still see each other.

723
00:43:09,333 --> 00:43:10,875
People do.

724
00:43:10,875 --> 00:43:14,000
We could arrange
shore leave together.

725
00:43:14,000 --> 00:43:17,917
And, for the future...
who knows?

726
00:43:17,917 --> 00:43:19,709
Of course.

727
00:43:33,250 --> 00:43:35,417
Promise me something.

728
00:43:35,417 --> 00:43:38,125
Don't give up your music.
